{{Non-free use rationale | Description = A speechless comic book scan showing a super-sized Ultimatum stomping on Miles Morales, his teenaged self. Written by Javier GarrÃ³n, David Curiel, Cory Petit, copyright Marvel Entertainment. | Source = Miles Morales Spider-Man Vol 1 #10 | Article = Miles Morales | Portion = Single comic book panel | Low_resolution = No | Purpose = This image serves as a primary identification of the subject (Character) of the intended section (Ultimatum), wearing a different supervillian cotsume in order to establish him as an alternative version of the article's subject. | Replaceability = There is no free version of this image, so it cannot be replaced by a free version | other_information = I don't know if I am using this template correctly and cannot figure out how to link to a low res image and would like to know if I am not. After consideration I also feel I don't need both this and the below image in the same article, only one. The benefit of this specifically is establishing Ultimatum's supervillian identity and costume, which is in line with the usual theme of Comic characters in flashy costumes and immediately sets him apart visually from the heroic Miles. As well as his main equipment being Captain America's shield and Giant-Man's suit from the Ultimate Universe. If this image is chosen I want the caption to be: "The first appearance of Miles Morales as Ultimatum (Miles Morales: Spider-Man #10 November 2019)" }}

{{Non-free use rationale | Description = Concept artwork of the Crewmate character in Among Us | Source = Developer's twitter page (Marcus Bromander) | Article = Among Us | Portion = Unknown. This is the only public concept image and has been shared digitally. | Low_resolution = No | Purpose = Primary identification of the iconic crewmate character, as well as an illustration of the progress of its creation, as any simple image of a crewmate would lack purpose. | Replaceability = The image exists as reported on by Polygon, however it links to the same tweet. Comment: I don't think a valid non-free rationale can be provided for this. The image doesn't seem to fall under fair-use. If there was a seperate article for say "Characters of Among Us", then perhaps this image could be used.â€” Yours, Berrely â€¢ Talkâˆ•Contribs

Honestly, not sure what "Free" image is supposed to mean. There's a citation, copyright holder's names are available, it's been shared publically by them and reported on by news articles. Are you telling me I have to find an article that doesn't link to the tweet, but has a directly downloadable copy of the image? The Polygon article and one by Gamasutra were the only ones I could find https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/371552/Early_Among_Us_character_concepts_depict_the_birth_of_the_bean.php 2603:7000:1F00:6B91:DDD6:8F8F:7FA2:1CB4 (talk)

By free, it means freely usable media. On Wikipedia, "free" media is media that is under the same or a compatible license as Wikipedia, which is CC BY-SA 3.0. Non-free media is media that is not under a compatible license. The only times this content may be used is when there is explicit permission from the copyright holder, or a valid reason under fair-use. To learn more, see WP:F for more info â€” Yours, Berrely â€¢ Talkâˆ•Contribs
